    <text>
        <body>
            <div type="edition" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="la" resp="#AA">
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><persName type="attested"><name><unclear>M</unclear>ania</name> <persName type="patronym"><name><expan><abbr>L</abbr><ex>uci</ex></expan></name> <expan><abbr>f</abbr><ex>ilia</ex></expan></persName> <name>B<supplied reason="lost">e</supplied>tutia</name> <name><seg part="I">Pro</seg><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/></name></persName>
                    <lb n="2"/>flaminica <g ref="symbols.xml#interpunct">·</g> <persName type="divine" key="divaLivia"><name><unclear>d</unclear>ivae</name> <g ref="symbols.xml#interpunct">·</g> <name><expan><abbr>Aug</abbr><ex>ustae</ex></expan></name></persName> <g ref="symbols.xml#ivy-leaf">❦</g> <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="char"/>
                </ab>
            </div>
            <div type="apparatus">
                <listApp>
                    <app><note>Text from EDR, comparison with photographs</note></app>
                    <app loc="1"><note>As Boffo and Ambaglio (1992) note, the first character, although unclear, is undoubtedly an "A". There are a variety of ways to restore Pro[---] at the end of the line: Pro[cula], Pro[cilla], Pro[ba], Pro[cessa], Pro[pinqua], and Pro[futura] being just some of the options.</note></app>
                    <app loc="2"><note>Boffo and Ambaglio (1992) restore [f(aciendum) c(uravit)] at the end of line two, but this – while possible – is stretching the evidence a little too far.</note></app>
                </listApp>
            </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:lang="en" resp="#AA">
                <p>Mania Betutia Pro[---], daughter of Lucius, flaminica of the divine Augusta [---].</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                <p>As Granino Cecere (2014) suggests, it is possible that this once belonged to a small architrave of a building, perhaps a sacred site. Granino Cecere (2014); Bassignano (1994-1995) and Boffo and Ambaglio (1992) see this as a priesthood to the divine Livia (diva Augusta). There is a Manius elsewhere in Ticium (CIL 5.6445), and members of the Betutia family attested elsewhere.</p> 
            </div>
